[
    {
        "content": "<p>Spinning off of <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"231634\" href=\"/#narrow/stream/231634-beginners/topic/Code.20review.3F\">#beginners &gt; Code review?</a>, there were a few messages (<a href=\"#narrow/stream/231634-beginners/topic/Code.20review.3F/near/419008444\">start</a>, <a href=\"#narrow/stream/231634-beginners/topic/Code.20review.3F/near/419078491\">end</a>) around how it would be nice for <code>Num.absDiff</code> to always return an unsigned number.</p>\n<p>This has a few advantages:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>It has a wider range of outputs for signed types. <code>Num.absDiff -1 Num.maxI32</code> would work.</li>\n<li>Related to 1, it will never panic</li>\n<li>It is more truthful about the output type. End users will know that negative outputs are impossible.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In the current Roc type system, Signed and Unsigned numbers are not usefully distinguishable in a related way. There is no way to know that U8 and I8 are related and transform from one to the other.</p>\n<p>I think we should restructure the Num type to support signedness.</p>\n<p>Current I8 looks like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">range</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Integer</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">range</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"kt\">I8</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Signed8</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I propose that we separate the signedness from the bitwidth. There are multiple ways to do this. The most directly probably being:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">I8</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Signed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Bits8</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>With that type, a user could write:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">absDiff</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">sign</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">bits</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">sign</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">bits</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Unsigned</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">bits</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Of course we will need a <code>Num.toSigned</code> and <code>Num.toUnsigned</code> or similar to support this, but I think it would be a great help to the type system.</p>\n<p>Thoughts?</p>",
        "id": 419083378,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706720091
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I thought about this initially (it can be done with <code>Int</code> still having one type variable by using a record, e.g. <code>Int { sign, bits }</code>, so then other functions can still have <code>Int a, Int a -&gt; ...</code>) but I ended up concluding it wasn't worth the complexity given how rarely it comes up</p>",
        "id": 419123682,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706735364
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what other use cases would this have besides <code>absDiff</code>?</p>",
        "id": 419123707,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706735378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I ran into it while fuzzing, but yeah it is pretty rare.</p>",
        "id": 419123866,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706735443
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I had a function where I wanted to be able to accept any unsigned integer as input.</p>",
        "id": 419124116,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706735577
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Cause the function would give totally incorrect results for signed numbers.</p>",
        "id": 419124156,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706735597
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>do you remember what it was for?</p>",
        "id": 419124348,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706735687
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, it was for generating a random integer in between two values from fuzz input. How the algorithm works, you essentially have to convert to unsigned, run the algorithm, then convert back to signed.</p>",
        "id": 419124554,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706735787
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actual rust algorithm for reference: <a href=\"https://github.com/rust-fuzz/arbitrary/blob/803f2df52fabe3a630fb054b8d7e7e2795487971/src/unstructured.rs#L303-L373\">https://github.com/rust-fuzz/arbitrary/blob/803f2df52fabe3a630fb054b8d7e7e2795487971/src/unstructured.rs#L303-L373</a></p>",
        "id": 419139214,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706742046
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note the <code>to_unsigned</code> and <code>from_unsigned</code> calls</p>",
        "id": 419139252,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706742066
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, looking at the impl in more detail now, What the rust author did to support this was implement a trait on all the rust integer types. Technically the Roc number types are opaque. So theoretically an ability could be used if new abilities where allowed to be added to any opaque type.</p>",
        "id": 419140479,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706742637
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah I strongly want to avoid that though <span aria-label=\"big smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f604\" role=\"img\" title=\"big smile\">:big_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 419149377,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706747337
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, ik. Just noting how it was dealt with in rust and what a direct translation would be.</p>",
        "id": 419149426,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706747368
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Too bad I can just comptime match on a type variable.</p>",
        "id": 419149466,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706747402
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">signed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Bool</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">signed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">comptime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">when</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">is</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kt\">Signed8</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Signed16</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">...</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Bool</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">true</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kt\">Unsigned8</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Unsigned16</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">...</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Bool</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">false</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 419149634,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706747518
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>with compile-time evaluation of constants that would Just Work</p>",
        "id": 419168787,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706759496
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Only if we add the ability to match on a type variable in general</p>",
        "id": 419169775,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706759907
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh I missed that part nm</p>",
        "id": 419261327,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706798697
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess if you wanted to keep at most one type variable for simplicity, it could be:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Integer</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kt\">SInt</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Integer</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Signed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">))</span>\n\n<span class=\"kt\">UInt</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Integer</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Unsigned</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">))</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Would something along those lines work?</p>",
        "id": 419273485,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706801982
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course we don't have to actually expose and <code>SInt</code> or <code>UInt</code> alias. It could be required to write</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">Int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Signed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 419273744,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706802046
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah that could also work</p>",
        "id": 419306516,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706811425
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but overall I think the bar for making such a fundamental type more complicated is higher than the number of motivating use cases right now <span aria-label=\"big smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f604\" role=\"img\" title=\"big smile\">:big_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 419306616,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706811468
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>especially considering it's more work for the type checker</p>",
        "id": 419306704,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1706811499
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, at least we have an implementation that might work if we even gain enough motivating use cases.</p>",
        "id": 419310482,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1706812832
    }
]